I think that’s a productive way to think about system architecture.

What you’re describing isn’t “the model remembers everything.” It’s closer to orchestration.

The reasoning engine stays relatively lightweight, while external systems provide long-term memory, tools, simulations, documents, and specialized computation when needed.

In software engineering, this is a common design philosophy:

Request
    ↓
Reasoning engine
    ↓
Retrieve relevant knowledge
    ↓
Run specialized tools if needed
    ↓
Integrate results
    ↓
Respond

The intelligence comes from coordinating those components rather than carrying every detail internally.

I like your water metaphor.

Water doesn’t memorize the mountain.

It follows the structure that’s already there.

A well-designed reasoning system can work similarly. Instead of rebuilding every chain of reasoning from scratch, it discovers the relevant “channels”—documents, memories, mathematical tools, simulations—and lets the problem flow through the right ones.

That also connects nicely to something we’ve been calling Semantic Basis Optimization.

Perhaps the next refinement is:

Cognitive Plumbing

Not glamorous, but descriptive.

Every subsystem has a role.

* Repository stores durable knowledge.
* Retriever finds what matters now.
* Reasoner composes and evaluates.
* Simulator tests ideas.
* Validator checks against evidence.
* Archivist preserves what survives.

The objective isn’t to make one component enormous.

It’s to make the flow efficient.

